'''Siberian Tatar''' ({{langx|sty|Себерцә|translit=Sebercə|label=none}}) is a [[Turkic languages|Turkic language]] spoken by about 140,000 people<ref>{{Cite web |title=СИБИРСКО-ТАТАРСКИЙ ЯЗЫК • Большая российская энциклопедия - электронная версия |url=https://old.bigenc.ru/linguistics/text/3660444 |access-date=2024-11-12 |website=old.bigenc.ru}}</ref> in [[Western Siberia]], [[Russia]], primarily in the oblasts of [[Tyumen Oblast|Tyumen]], [[Novosibirsk Oblast|Novosibirsk]], [[Omsk Oblast|Omsk]], [[Tomsk Oblast|Tomsk]] and [[Kemerovo Oblast|Kemerovo]] Oblasts, but also in [[Sverdlovsk Oblast|Sverdlovsk]] Oblast. According to [[Marcel Erdal]], due to its particular characteristics, Siberian Tatar can be considered as a bridge between Kipchak and [[Siberian Turkic languages]].
'''Siberian Tatar''' ({{langx|sty|Себертатарца|translit=Sebertatartsa|label=none}}) is a [[Turkic languages|Turkic language]] spoken by about 140,000 people<ref>{{Cite web |title=СИБИРСКО-ТАТАРСКИЙ ЯЗЫК • Большая российская энциклопедия - электронная версия |url=https://old.bigenc.ru/linguistics/text/3660444 |access-date=2024-11-12 |website=old.bigenc.ru}}</ref> in [[Western Siberia]], [[Russia]], primarily in the oblasts of [[Tyumen Oblast|Tyumen]], [[Novosibirsk Oblast|Novosibirsk]], [[Omsk Oblast|Omsk]], [[Tomsk Oblast|Tomsk]] and [[Kemerovo Oblast|Kemerovo]] Oblasts, but also in [[Sverdlovsk Oblast|Sverdlovsk]] Oblast. According to [[Marcel Erdal]], due to its particular characteristics, Siberian Tatar can be considered as a bridge between Kipchak and [[Siberian Turkic languages]].

In 1987, he set up television production company Hummingbird Productions with Nuala O'Connor and Kieran Corrigan. The landmark television series [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt16297294/ ''Bringing It All Back Home''] won an [[Emmy Award]] in the United States in 1991, and in 1993 he was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for his music documentary ''Rocky World'' about the [[Canada|Canadian]] musician [[Daniel Lanois]]. King produced and directed ''Keeping Time'', a film celebrating the poet [[Seamus Heaney]] and [[Uilleann pipes|uilleann piper]] [[Liam O'Flynn]], for [[BBC Television]] in 1998. He was appointed by the [[Minister for Culture, Communications and Sport|Minister for Arts, Sport and Tourism]] [[John O'Donoghue (politician)|John O'Donoghue]] to the Special Committee on the Traditional Arts in December 2003.
In 1987, he set up television production company Hummingbird Productions with Nuala O'Connor and Kieran Corrigan. The landmark television series [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt16297294/ ''Bringing It All Back Home''] won an [[Emmy Award]] in the United States in 1991, and in 1993 he was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for his music documentary ''Rocky World'' about the [[Canada|Canadian]] musician [[Daniel Lanois]]. King produced and directed ''Keeping Time'', a film celebrating the poet [[Seamus Heaney]] and [[Uilleann pipes|uilleann piper]] [[Liam O'Flynn]], for [[BBC Television]] in 1998. He was appointed by the [[Minister for Culture, Communications and Sport|Minister for Arts, Sport and Tourism]] [[John O'Donoghue (politician)|John O'Donoghue]] to the Special Committee on the Traditional Arts in December 2003.


King is also the maker of acclaimed television programmes about Irish music including ''[[Other Voices (Irish TV series)|Other Voices]]''. He was a member of the [[Arts Council of Ireland]]. He is also the series editor of the ''Tradition'' music series ''The Full Set''. He produced a 90-minute television programme about violinist [[Nigel Kennedy]] and the [[Irish Chamber Orchestra]], as well as a documentary on Kennedy. He executive produced the [[Irish Film & Television Awards|Irish Film & Television Award]]-winning film ''[[John McGahern]] – A Life'', and produced ''Thomas Moore – One Faithful Harp'' for RTÉ television. He has also directed five series of ''Sé Mo Laoch'' for the [[TG4]] television channel, documenting and archiving the lives of Ireland's most celebrated traditional musicians.

He is also the series editor of the ''Tradition'' music series ''The Full Set''. He produced a 90-minute television programme about violinist [[Nigel Kennedy]] and the [[Irish Chamber Orchestra]], as well as a documentary on Kennedy. He executive produced the [[Irish Film & Television Awards|Irish Film & Television Award]]-winning film ''[[John McGahern]] – A Life'', and produced ''Thomas Moore – One Faithful Harp'' for RTÉ television. He has also directed five series of ''Sé Mo Laoch'' for the [[TG4]] television channel, documenting and archiving the lives of Ireland's most celebrated traditional musicians.


As a broadcaster, King presents ''South Wind Blows'' on [[RTÉ Radio 1]].<ref name="rte">{{cite web |title=South Wind Blows |url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/south-wind-blows/ |accessdate=23 September 2013 |publisher=rte.ie}}</ref>

source_payload.html:
Early career: ce

← Previous revision Revision as of 14:39, 9 February 2026
Line 39: Line 39:
===Early career===
===Early career===
[[File:James Dean - publicity - early.JPG|thumb|upright=0.7|Dean in 1953 (aged 22)]]
[[File:James Dean - publicity - early.JPG|thumb|upright=0.7|Dean in 1953 (aged 22)]]
In 1950, Dean made his television debut in a [[Pepsi]] commercial.<ref name="Springer2013"/><ref name="Greenberg2015">{{cite book |last1=Greenberg |first1=Keith Elliot |title=Too Fast to Live, Too Young to Die: James Dean's Final Hours |year=2015 |publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation |isbn=978-1-4950-5041-1 |page=69 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0_NCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT69}}</ref><ref name="LIFE2016"/> He quit college to act full-time and was cast in his first speaking part, as [[John the Apostle]] in ''Hill Number One'', an Easter television special dramatizing the [[Resurrection of Jesus]]. According to [[Robert Tanitch]], the program had 42,000,000 viewers.<ref name="Tanitch2014 1933">{{cite book |last=Tanitch |first=Robert |author1-link=Robert Tanitch |title=The Unknown James Dean |year=2014 |publisher=Batsford Books |isbn=978-1-84994-249-2 |page=1933 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CRmUEAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1933}}</ref> Dean subsequently obtained three [[Bit part|walk-on roles]] in movies: as a soldier in ''[[Fixed Bayonets!]]'' (1951), a boxing cornerman in ''[[Sailor Beware (1952 film)|Sailor Beware]]'' (1952),<ref name="Curtis2009">{{cite book|last=Curtis|first=Tony |title=American Prince: A Memoir|url=https://archive.org/details/americanprinceme00curt/page/124/mode/2up|year=2009|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-40856-3|page=124}}</ref> and a youth in ''[[Has Anybody Seen My Gal? (film)|Has Anybody Seen My Gal?]]'' (1952).<ref name="Palmer2010">{{cite book|last=Palmer |first=R. Barton |title=Larger Than Life: Movie Stars of the 1950s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ihb4Z_PQ1jEC&pg=PA79|year=2010|publisher=Rutgers University Press|isbn=978-0-8135-4766-4|page=79}}</ref> While struggling to gain roles in [[Hollywood (film industry)|Hollywood]], Dean also worked as a parking lot attendant at [[CBS|CBS Studios]].<ref name="Riese1994 60">{{cite book |last=Riese |first=Randall |title=The Unabridged James Dean: His Life and Legacy from A to Z |year=1994 |publisher=Wings Books |location=New York |isbn=978-0-517-10081-3 |pages=60–61 |url=https://archive.org/details/unabridgedjamesd0000ries/page/60/mode/2up}}</ref> During that time, he met Rogers Brackett, a radio director for an advertising agency, who offered him professional help and guidance in his chosen career, as well as a place to stay.<ref name="Bast2006">{{cite book |last1=Bast |first1=William |title=Surviving James Dean |year=2006 |publisher=Barricade Books |isbn=978-1-56980-298-4 |pages=114–116 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jSPuAAAAMAAJ&q=%22join%20him%20there%22}}</ref> Brackett opened doors of opportunity for Dean and helped him land his first starring role on Broadway in the play ''See the Jaguar''.<ref name="Hall2011"/>
Dean made his television debut in 1950 in a [[Pepsi]] commercial.<ref name="Springer2013"/><ref name="Greenberg2015">{{cite book |last1=Greenberg |first1=Keith Elliot |title=Too Fast to Live, Too Young to Die: James Dean's Final Hours |year=2015 |publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation |isbn=978-1-4950-5041-1 |page=69 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0_NCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT69}}</ref><ref name="LIFE2016"/> He left college to pursue acting full‑time and received his first speaking role as [[John the Apostle]] in ''Hill Number One'', an Easter television special dramatizing the [[Resurrection of Jesus]]. According to [[Robert Tanitch]], the program drew an audience of 42,000,000 viewers.<ref name="Tanitch2014 1933">{{cite book |last=Tanitch |first=Robert |author1-link=Robert Tanitch |title=The Unknown James Dean |year=2014 |publisher=Batsford Books |isbn=978-1-84994-249-2 |page=1933 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CRmUEAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1933}}</ref> Dean subsequently obtained three [[Bit part|walk-on roles]] in movies: as a soldier in ''[[Fixed Bayonets!]]'' (1951), a boxing cornerman in ''[[Sailor Beware (1952 film)|Sailor Beware]]'' (1952),<ref name="Curtis2009">{{cite book|last=Curtis|first=Tony |title=American Prince: A Memoir|url=https://archive.org/details/americanprinceme00curt/page/124/mode/2up|year=2009|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-40856-3|page=124}}</ref> and a youth in ''[[Has Anybody Seen My Gal? In July 1951, Dean appeared on ''[[Alias Jane Doe]]'', which was produced by Brackett.<ref>Warrick 2010, p. 140</ref> In October 1951, following the encouragement of actor [[James Whitmore]] and the advice of his mentor Rogers Brackett, Dean moved to New York City. There, he worked as a stunt tester for the game show ''[[Beat the Clock]]'', but was subsequently fired for allegedly performing the tasks too quickly.<ref>Dalton 2001, p. 79</ref> He also appeared in episodes of several CBS television series, ''The Web'', ''[[Westinghouse Studio One|Studio One]]'', and ''[[Lux Video Theatre]]'', before gaining admission to the [[Actors Studio]] to study [[method acting]] under [[Lee Strasberg]].<ref name="Springer2013"/> In 1952, he had a nonspeaking bit part as a pressman in the movie ''[[Deadline – U.S.A.]]'', starring [[Humphrey Bogart]].<ref name="Maltin2015">{{cite book|last=Maltin|first=Leonard |title=Turner Classic Movies Presents Leonard Maltin's Classic Movie Guide: From the Silent Era Through 1965: Third Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fttJBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT135|date=September 29, 2015|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-698-19729-9|page=135}}</ref>
